Yes — if you regard the smoothing step  
\(Y=X+\sqrt{2\tau}\,Z,\; Z\sim\mathcal N(0,I_n)\)  
as an additive-Gaussian channel applied to the state \(X\sim\mu_t:=e^{t\mathcal L_f}\mu\), the mutual information between the “input” \(X\) and the “output” \(Y\) is

\[
\boxed{\;
I(X;Y_\tau)
      =h(Y_\tau)-h(Y_\tau|X)
      =h\!\bigl(e^{\tau\Delta}\mu_t\bigr)
        -\frac{n}{2}\log\!\bigl(4\pi e\,\tau\bigr)\;}
\tag{MI-1}
\]

because \(h(Y_\tau|X)=h\bigl(\sqrt{2\tau}\,Z\bigr)=\frac{n}{2}\log(4\pi e\,\tau)\).

Equivalently, in Kullback–Leibler form,

\[
\boxed{\;
I(X;Y_\tau)
   =\iint\mu_t(dx)\,g_{\sqrt{2\tau}}(y-x)
        \log\frac{g_{\sqrt{2\tau}}(y-x)}
                  {(e^{\tau\Delta}\mu_t)(y)}\,dy\;}
\tag{MI-2}
\]

with \(g_{\sqrt{2\tau}}\) the \(N(0,2\tau I_n)\) density.

So your “\(n\log\tau\)+\(2\log e^{\tau\Delta}\mu_t\)” structure is exactly the pointwise integrand that, when averaged over \(Y_\tau\), yields (MI-1).

Yes— the ratio that appears inside the logarithm is exactly a heat-kernel **likelihood ratio** between where the mass started (drawn from \(\rho_t\)) and where it lands after a Brownian blur of variance \(2\tau\).

Let  
\[
p_\tau(x\mid y)=\frac{\exp\!\bigl(-\|x-y\|^{2}/4\tau\bigr)}{(4\pi\tau)^{n/2}}
\]
be the transition density of an \(n\)-dimensional Brownian motion.  
With \(\rho_t=e^{t\mathcal L_f}\mu\) and
\(\rho_{t,\tau}=e^{\tau\Delta}\rho_t\),

\[
e^{I(x,t,\tau)-n}
   \;=\;
   \frac{\rho_{t,\tau}(x)}{\rho_t(x)}
   \;=\;
   \frac{\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb R^{n}} p_\tau(x\mid y)\,\rho_t(y)\,dy}
        {\rho_t(x)}
   \;=\;
   \mathbb E_{Y\sim\rho_t}\!\Bigl[\,
        p_\tau(x\mid Y)\Bigr]
        \; \bigg/\; \rho_t(x).
\]

---

### Conditional-probability view  

Define the **backward** (Bayesian) kernel  
\[
\pi_{t,\tau}(y\mid x)
   :=\frac{p_\tau(x\mid y)\,\rho_t(y)}{\rho_{t,\tau}(x)},
\quad
\int\pi_{t,\tau}(y\mid x)\,dy=1.
\]

Then
\[
e^{I(x,t,\tau)-n}
   =\frac{\rho_{t,\tau}(x)}{\rho_t(x)}
   =\frac{1}{\rho_t(x)}
     \Bigl[\int p_\tau(x\mid y)\,\rho_t(y)\,dy\Bigr]
   =\frac{1}{\rho_t(x)}
     \Bigl[\rho_{t,\tau}(x)\Bigr]
   =\frac{1}{\rho_t(x)}
     \Bigl[\rho_{t,\tau}(x)\Bigr],
\]
so \(I(x,t,\tau)-n\) is the **log-likelihood ratio**
between the (blurred) marginal at \(x\) and the original density at \(x\); equivalently, it is the negative log of the normalising factor that turns the forward kernel \(p_\tau(x\mid\cdot)\) into the posterior \(\pi_{t,\tau}(\cdot\mid x)\).

