No extra \(1/8\) is needed—the factor is already implicit in the weights.  
Write the operator in either of the two algebraically equivalent forms

\[
\boxed{\;
\mathscr L\rho_{ij}= \sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}} w_{ij,i'j'}\,\rho_{i'j'}-\rho_{ij}
\;}
\qquad\Longleftrightarrow\qquad
\boxed{\;
\mathscr L\rho_{ij}= \sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}}
         w_{ij,i'j'}\bigl(\rho_{i'j'}-\rho_{ij}\bigr)
\;}
\]

provided the weights satisfy the *normalisation* condition

\[
\sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}} w_{ij,i'j'} = 1 .
\]

---

### Where the \(1/8\) goes

For the equal-weight Moore stencil one has \(w_{ij,i'j'}=\tfrac18\).  
In the “difference–inside–the–sum’’ form this gives

\[
\mathscr L\rho_{ij}= \frac18\sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}}
        \bigl(\rho_{i'j'}-\rho_{ij}\bigr)
      = \frac18\sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}}\rho_{i'j'}
        -\Bigl(\tfrac18\!\sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}}1\Bigr)\rho_{ij}
      = \frac18\sum_{(i',j')\in\mathcal N_{ij}}\rho_{i'j'}-\rho_{ij}.
\]

So the centre value is subtracted **once**, not \(1/8\) times, because  
\(\sum w_{ij,i'j'} = 1\).  You can keep the \(\rho_{ij}\) term outside the sum (first box) or distribute it inside with its weight (second box); the two expressions are identical.

If the stencil uses unequal weights (e.g.\ the \(1/6\)–\(1/12\) nine-point Laplacian) the same algebra works because the weights are still normalised to one.  Therefore the paper’s notation with a single “\(-\rho_{ij}\)” is perfectly consistent, and no standalone \(1/8\) factor is missing.
